# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: s-hertogenbosch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The **158th Infantry Brigade** was an infantry brigade of the British Army that served in both the First and Second World Wars, before being disbanded in 1968.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] Throughout its existence the brigade was assigned to the 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division and was composed almost entirely of Territorial battalions from the Royal Welch Fusiliers.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The brigade was assigned to the Welsh Division, one of fourteen divisions of the peacetime Territorial Force.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] As the name suggests, the brigade recruited primarily from North Wales.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The Welsh Division was mobilised on 5 August 1914, the day after Britain declared war on Germany, which officially began the First World War.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] According to the Territorial and Reserve Forces Act 1907 soldiers of the Territorial Force were only able to serve overseas with their permission and so, when asked, a large majority of the men volunteered for overseas service.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] Throughout 1915 all divisions of the Territorial Force were given numbers and so, on 13 May 1915, the division was numbered as the 53rd (Welsh) Division and all the brigades of the division were also numbered, the North Wales Brigade becoming the **158th (1/1st North Wales) Brigade**.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The brigade fought with the 53rd (Welsh) Division throughout the First World War in the Middle Eastern theatre from mid-1915 until the end of the war in 1918.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] In its first action the brigade was involved in the disastrous Gallipoli Campaign where it landed in August 1915.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] After temporarily serving under command of the 2nd Mounted Division, between 31 October and 28 November, the brigade, together with the rest of 53rd Division, was evacuated form Gallipoli to Egypt in December 1915 and continued serving in the Middle Eastern theatre in Sinai and Palestine.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The brigade took part in the Battle of Romani in August 1916, the Battle of El Buggar Ridge in October 1917 and the action of Tell 'Asur in March 1918, where it fought off several counter-attacks by the Ottoman forces.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] Throughout mid-1918, most of the British battalions of the brigade were posted to reinforce the British Expeditionary Force (BEF) serving in the trenches of the Western Front, after the German Army launched its huge Spring Offensive, which saw huge territorial gains for the Germans.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] As a result, the British battalions were replaced by Indian Army battalions.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] This occurred in most British divisions serving in the Middle East.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The division and brigade, along with the rest of the Territorial Force, was disbanded after the war but started to reform in 1920, and was later renamed the Territorial Army.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The division was reformed as the 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division and the brigade was itself reformed and renamed as the **158th (Royal Welch) Infantry Brigade**, with its headquarters at Wrexham.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The brigade again consisted of four battalions of the Royal Welch Fusiliers and this remained the order of battle of the brigade for most of the inter-war period.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] In 1938 a reorganisation of the Territorial Army's infantry divisions saw them reduced from twelve to nine infantry battalions.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The Territorial Army, and 53rd Division, was mobilised in late August/early September 1939, due to the situation in Europe becoming increasingly worse.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The German Army invaded Poland on 1 September 1939 and Britain and France declared war on Germany two days later, officially beginning the Second World War.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] Over a month later, in October the brigade, as in the First World War consisted of three battalions of the Royal Welch Fusiliers, the 4th, 6th and 7th.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The 158th Brigade the first element of the 53rd Division to be sent to Northern Ireland, followed in December by the 160th Brigade and later 159th Brigade in April 1940.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The brigade would remain there until November 1941, training hard with the rest of the division.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] In November 1941 the division was sent back to the mainland again, briefly serving in Wales before transferring to Kent, coming under command of XII Corps and training alongside 43rd (Wessex) and 46th Infantry Divisions.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] At the time the corps was commanded by Lieutenant-General Bernard Montgomery.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] 53rd (Welsh) Division spent the next few years training for the planned Allied invasion of Normandy (Operation Overlord).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] The intensity of training was stepped up in 1944.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] Early in the year the division was involved in two corps-level exercises.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] In March divisional HQ and the brigade and ancillary HQs took part in 'Exercise Shudder' to study 'thrust line' technique, then in April the whole division was engaged in 'Exercise Henry' on the South Downs training area; this included a river crossing and full-scale simulated attack.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] In May 'Exercise Bud' practised loading vehicles onto landing craft.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] Finally, in the last week of May, the brigade began moving into its concentration area ready for the invasion.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] During operations undertaken by the 158th Brigade to close the Falaise Pocket, heavy fighting took place on 16 August around the town of Balfour.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] During this action, Captain Tasker Watkins, commanding B Company of the 1/5th Battalion, Welch Regiment, personally led a charge across a heavily defended stretch of open ground, reaching and personally eliminating an enemy position in spite of his companies' very heavy losses.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/158th-infantry-brigade-united-kingdom] For this action, he received the Victoria Cross.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The **1984 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the XXIII Olympiad** and commonly known as **Los Angeles 1984**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 28 to August 12, 1984, in Los Angeles, California, United States.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] It was the second time that Los Angeles had hosted the Games, with the first in 1932.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] California was the home state of the incumbent U.S. president Ronald Reagan, who officially opened the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] These were the first Summer Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Juan Antonio Samaranch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Albania, Iran, Libya and Upper Volta also chose to boycott the Games, but for unrelated reasons.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Despite the field being depleted in certain sports due to the boycott, 140 National Olympic Committees took part in the 1984 Games, a record number at the time.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and overall medals, followed by Romania and West Germany.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The 1984 Summer Olympics are widely considered to be the most financially successful modern Olympics, serving as a model on how to run an Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] As a result of low construction costs, due to the use of existing sport infrastructure, coupled with a reliance on private corporate funding, the 1984 Games generated a profit of US $232.5 million (equivalent to US $592.25 million in 2024).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will host the Summer Olympics for the third time in 2028, becoming the third city in the world—following London and Paris—to do so.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] After the terrorist attack at the 1972 Summer Olympics, the significant financial debts of Montreal (1976), and various boycotts by National Olympic Committees, few cities by the late 1970s were willing to bid for the Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Only two cities (Tehran and Los Angeles) made serious bids for the 1984 Summer Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Tehran submitted its bid to host the 1984 Summer Olympics to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) on 29 August 1975.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The selection of the host city was made at the 80th IOC Session in Athens on 18 May 1978, where Los Angeles was chosen as the host city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Los Angeles had unsuccessfully bid for the two previous Summer Olympic Games (1976 and 1980, which went to Montreal and Moscow, respectively).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The United States Olympic Committee (USOC) had submitted at least one bid for every Olympics since 1944 but had not succeeded since the Los Angeles Olympics in 1932, the previous time only a single bid had been issued for the Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] In 1977, the USOC selected Los Angeles over New York City to be the American candidate for the 1984 Summer Olympics in a 55–39 vote.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee (LAOOC) was officially established on June 15, 1978, to manage the games using private funds rather than public debt.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Peter Ueberroth was selected as President of the LAOOC in early 1979.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Using UCLA student housing as the primary village.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] UCLA hosted 4,000 athletes, along with USC, it hosted swimmers and UCSB hosted the rowing teams.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] LAOOC had to prepare for twenty-six competition venues.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Twenty of the competition venues were existing, three were new: the Olympic Velodrome on the California State University, Dominguez Hills campus, Prado Park for shooting and the Olympic Swim Stadium on the University of Southern California campus.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Velodrome was constructed between 1981 and 1982, while the Swim Stadium was constructed between 1980 and 1983.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] 7-Eleven convenience stores sponsored the Velodrome, while McDonald's sponsored the Swim Stadium, though neither corporate name was mentioned in the official Olympic report.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The three temporary venues were set up at Fairbanks Ranch Country Club for equestrian, Long Beach shoreline for sailing and Lake Casitas for rowing.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Games cost a total of $546 million ($1.7 billion in 2026).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The LAOOC calculated early on, it would have to make six times the revenue of previous games from sponsorship, television rights, and ticket sales.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Ueberroth auctioned off sponsorship rights for each product area and required each sponsor to make a minimum contribution of $4 million as a in-kind donation to the LAOOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] For example, Coca-Cola beat out Pepsi for the soft drink sponsorship area by paying $12.6 million.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] When Kodak persisted in offering only half of Ueberroth’s $4 million minimum for the film supply sponsorship, the LAOOC offered Fuji Film seventy-two hours to sign a contract - which resulted in a $7 million deal.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] These sponsorships were sold in record amounts and covered the majority of the Games' expenditures.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] All revenues were immediately deposited into interest bearing accounts, which due to the high interest rates of that period (in excess of 20% in 1979) yielded most of the operating budget for the LAOOC into the early 1980s.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] At the time, the largest local and federal security force was assembled due to prior Olympic games security failures, primarily the events in Munich.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Los Angeles Police Department, federal agents and thousands of temporary security agents were tasked to provide safety at each event.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Security was the most expensive item on the budget.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] LAOOC provided $35 million and the federal government provided $50 million each.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The rest was covered by the city and state government.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The California Highway Patrol was responsible for the security of visiting dignitaries, including President Ronald Reagan.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Security planning was marred by unresolved disputes between the FBI and the Los Angeles Police Department, both of which claimed the right to take lead control incase of an incident.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Los Angeles County's SCRTD was tasked to coordinate games movement, including transporting the "olympic family" of athletes, coaches, officials and media.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] SCRTD was operating the nation’s largest all-bus system in the 1980s.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] LAOOC and SCRTD coordinated a 550 special olympic bus fleet, including 24 shuttle services, dedicated express lanes and multiple park-and-ride routes.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Los Angeles had no public rail transit in 1984, the red car Pacific Electric rail network, the largest in the world, was dismantled by 1963.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] City leaders advised Angelenos to opt out of driving during the games or alter their driving habits and work hours.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley and LAOOC prepared an advertising informational campaign push called, "Take the Bus".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Bus schedules were provided to early bird ticket buyers to provide options on transportation to events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] During the games, more than 1 million boarding passengers heeded his message.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Predictions of gridlock and heavy smog never materialized.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The 1984 Summer Olympics was preceded by the 10-week-long adjunct Olympic Arts Festival or the Cultural Olympics, which opened on June 1 and ended on August 12.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] It provided more than 400 performances by 146 theater, dance, and music companies, representing every continent and 18 countries, as well as art exhibitions and films.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] It was organized by then-CalArts President Robert Fitzpatrick.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Along with many famous American dance companies, such as the Dance Theatre of Harlem, the festival hosted three international debuts: German choreographer Pina Bausch and her Tanztheater Wuppertal, Groupe Emile Dubois from France, and the Japanese Butoh.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Local Los Angeles artist Rodolfo Escalera was commissioned to create nine paintings depicting the Summer Games that would later be turned into collectible plates and presented as "The Official Gift of the 1984 Olympics".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] LAOOC also designated Ernie Barnes as "Sports Artist of the 1984 Summer Olympic Games" and Barnes was commissioned to create five Olympic-themed paintings and serve as an official Olympic spokesman to encourage inner-city youth.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] John Williams composed the theme for the Olympiad, "Los Angeles Olympic Theme" later also known as "Olympic Fanfare and Theme".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] This piece won a Grammy for Williams and became one of the most well-known musical themes of the Olympic Games, along with Leo Arnaud's "Bugler's Dream"; the latter is sometimes attached to the beginning of Olympic Fanfare and Theme.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Composer Bill Conti also wrote a song to inspire the weightlifters called "Power".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] An album, *The Official Music of the XXIII Olympiad—Los Angeles 1984*, featured tracks with sports themes written for the occasion by popular musical artists including Foreigner, Toto, Loverboy, Herbie Hancock, Quincy Jones, Christopher Cross, Philip Glass, Paul Engemann and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] "Reach Out" was the main soundtrack and is the official theme song of the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Brazilian composer Sérgio Mendes produced a special song for the 1984 Olympic Games, "Olympia," from his 1984 album *Confetti*.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] A choir of approximately one thousand voices was assembled of singers in the region.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] All were volunteers from nearby churches, schools and universities.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Pop-punk band Bowling for Soup references the games in the song "I Can't Stand LA".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] In the same week that the Games began, British pop star Howard Jones released a single called "Like to Get to Know You Well" which eventually made number 4 on the UK Singles Chart and number 49 on the Billboard Hot 100 in the United States.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] On the sleeve, the record was "dedicated to the original spirit of the Olympic Games".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The 1984 Olympic Torch Relay began in New York City and ended in Los Angeles, traversing 33 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Unlike later torch relays, the torch was continuously carried by runners on foot.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The route covered more than 9,320 mi (15,000 km) and involved 3,636 runners.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The cross country relay raised $10.31 million for charity (about $33 million in 2026).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Gina Hemphill, a granddaughter of Jesse Owens, carried the torch into the Coliseum, completed a lap around the track, then handed it off to the final runner, Rafer Johnson, winner of the decathlon at the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] With the torch, he touched off the flame which passed through a specially designed flammable Olympic rings.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Johnson became the first person of African descent to light the cauldron in Olympic history.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The flame then passed up to the cauldron atop the peristyle and remained aflame for the duration of the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Tickets were initially sold through an early access mail-in order form, lottery-style system on June 20, 1983.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Sears, Manufacturers Hanover Corporation and First Interstate Bank provided mail-in order forms and brochures to the public.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Sears was as a major distributor with 3,300 stores throughout the US.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Ticket management and advertisement was run by IMG.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Tickets sales in Southern California were sold separately.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] A total of 6.8 million tickets went on sale to the public with prices ranging from $3 to $95.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Opening and Closing ceremonies ranged from $50, $100 and $200 per ticket.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] A record 5.7 million tickets were sold, or 83% of capacity.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The remaining tickets were sold to "olympic family" members, sponsors or sold to corporations.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The emblem was designed by local design firm Robert Miles Runyan & Associates unveiled on August 4, 1980.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The "Stars and Motion" features three red, white, and blue stars representing first, second, and third place, intertwined with 13 horizontal stripes to convey speed and American pride.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The "Look of the Games," was designed by Jon Jerde and Deborah Sussman of Sussman/Prejza & Co.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] They designed an aesthetic known as "festive federalism".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Sussman created an eleven-color palette scheme for the games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] It utilized bright, unconventional colors combined with geometric shapes, stars, and banners to create a celebratory, cost-effective, and a unified visual identity across distant city venues.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Colors were chosen to represent the "California spirit", Latin-American influences in LA and Mediterranean influences in the Olympic movement, primarily Greece.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The 1984 Games were the first to use colorful themed graphics at every venue and field of play.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The term “Look of the Games” came into common usage as a result of Los Angeles’ innovative design program.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The mascot was a bald eagle named Sam the Olympic Eagle.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] LAOOC utilized a "free-enterprise" model, featuring 34 exclusive corporate sponsors that contributed over $126 million ($430 million in 2026), marking a shift toward high-stakes sponsorship.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Sponsors, licensees, and suppliers were allowed to use the Olympics star-in-motion logo, the interlocking-rings symbol, and the official mascot.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The marketing team rounded up 64 suppliers, and 65 licensees.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] They also created hospitality centers, introducing the concept for the first time.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Official licensees handed over 10% in royalties on sales, and official suppliers provided the materials needed to run the games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Sears withdrew from being an official sponsor but was still granted rights to distribute forms applications at Sears stores nationwide as a partner, selling tickets to the games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Manufacturers Hanover also was not official but distributed tickets, in the New York City area.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] For television rights, ABC bid against CBS and NBC for the US rights to broadcast the games, they agreed to pay a total of $225 million.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Under the terms of the agreement, ABC paid $100 million for the basic rights to the games, of which one third went to the IOC, and two thirds went to the LAOOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The remainder $125 million went to the LAOOC for special transmission facilities, venue lighting and other venue equipment required for the broadcasts.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Athletes from 140 states competed at the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Eighteen states made their Olympic debut: Bahrain, Bangladesh, Bhutan, British Virgin Islands, Djibouti, Equatorial Guinea, The Gambia, Grenada, Mauritania, Mauritius, North Yemen, Oman, Qatar, Rwanda, Western Samoa, Solomon Islands, Tonga, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Zaire had previously competed at the 1968 Summer Olympics as *Congo-Kinshasa*.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China made its first appearance in a Summer Olympics since 1952, while for the first time the Republic of China team participated under the politically contrived name of *Chinese Taipei*.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] As a result of the Nagoya Resolution signed in 1979, and the designating the Republic of China (Taiwan) as Chinese Taipei, the People's Republic of China returned to the Summer Olympics for the first time since Helsinki 1952.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Military anthem of China was played for both teams during the opening ceremony.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union led the Warsaw Pact members and other Communist countries in a boycott of the Los Angeles Olympics, in retaliation for the U.S.-led boycott of the Moscow Olympics four years earlier (over the Soviet Union's invasion of Afghanistan in 1979).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The pretexts for the 1984 Soviet-led boycott were concerns over security, "chauvinistic sentiments" and "an anti-Soviet hysteria ... being whipped up" in the United States.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] However, a handful of communist countries disregarded the boycott and attended the Games anyway, among them Yugoslavia (host of the 1984 Winter Olympics), the People's Republic of China, and Romania (the only Warsaw Pact country that had opted to ignore the Soviet demands).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Romanian team received a particularly warm reception from the United States; when the Romanian athletes entered during the opening ceremonies, they were greeted by a standing ovation from the spectators, who were mostly U.S. citizens.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] This would turn out to be Romania's most successful Olympic Games – they won 53 medals, including 20 golds.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] In the table below, the number of athletes representing each state is shown in parentheses.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Albania, Iran, Libya and Upper Volta (changed to Burkina Faso following August 4) also missed the Los Angeles Olympics, citing political reasons, but these countries were not a part of the Soviet-led boycott.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Albania, Iran and Upper Volta were the only three countries to boycott both the 1980 and 1984 Summer Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] A document obtained in 2016 by The New York Times revealed the Soviet Union's plans for a statewide doping system in track and field in preparation for the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Dated prior to the country's decision to boycott the Games, the document detailed existing steroids operations of the program, along with suggestions for further enhancements.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] For the first time in history, the International Olympic Committee authorized the formal segments of the opening ceremony to be interspersed with the cultural segments.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The start of the event featured the arrival of Bill Suitor by means of the Bell Aerosystems rocket pack (also known as a Jet Pack).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Etta James performed "When the Saints Go Marching In" at the Opening Ceremony.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Alongside Williams and the house orchestra, 84 pianists performed an abridged version of George Gershwin's composition *Rhapsody in Blue*.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Vicki McClure, along with the International Children's Choir of Long Beach, sang "Reach Out and Touch".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Lionel Richie performed a special extended 9-minute version of his hit single "All Night Long" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The United States topped the medal count for the first time since 1968, winning a record 83 gold medals and surpassing the Soviet Union's total of 80 golds at the 1980 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1984 Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] In the United States, the Games were broadcast by the American Broadcast Corporation (ABC), as part of a domestic deal with the LAOOC and with the IOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] It was the first time the IOC and a OCOG provided support for in-venue distribution.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] International television broadcasters and radio rights were acquired by 156 countries.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Following the news of the massive financial losses of the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal, the only two cities to express a genuine interest in hosting the 1984 Games were Los Angeles and New York.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Given that only one city per country is allowed to bid for any one Games, the USOC vote for the American bid city was effectively the deciding vote for the 1984 Olympics host city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] In this case, the Los Angeles bid received 55 votes compared with New York's 39 votes – this is the closest that the city of New York has ever come to being selected to host the Olympic Games, coming closer in 1984 than they did in their 2012 bid (when they lost to London).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Ambitious construction projects for the two previous Summer Olympics, Montreal 1976 and Moscow 1980, had burdened organizers with substantial debts as expenses greatly exceeded revenues.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Furthermore, the 1976 and 1980 Olympics were entirely government-funded.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Unlike Montreal and Moscow, Los Angeles 1984 was privately funded, with strict controls imposed on expenditure; rather than constructing new venues with overly ambitious designs, the organizers chose instead to utilize existing venues and facilities wherever possible.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The main example of this was the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, which was also the Olympic Stadium for the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The only two new venues constructed specifically for the 1984 Summer Olympics were secured with the backing of corporate sponsors: the Olympic Velodrome was largely funded by the 7-Eleven corporation and the Olympic Swim Stadium by McDonald's.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] In addition to corporate support, the Olympic committee also used the income from the exclusive television rights, and for the first time these contracts would prove to be a significant source of revenue.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Adjusted for inflation, the Los Angeles Games secured twice the amount of income received by the 1980 Moscow Summer Olympics and four times that of the 1976 Montreal Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The low level of interest among potential host cities for the 1984 Games had been viewed as a major threat to the future of the Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] However, after the financial success of the Los Angeles Games, cities began to show a renewed interest in bidding to become host again.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The Los Angeles and Montreal Games are seen as examples of best and worst practice when organizing the Olympics and serve as valuable lessons to prospective host cities.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The total surplus was US $232.5 million (equivalent to US $592.25 million in 2024).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Under the agreement made in 1979, 40 percent of any surplus was to stay in Southern California, with the other 60 percent going to the United States Olympic Committee.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The LA84 Foundation was founded as a private, nonprofit institution created by the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee to manage Southern California's endowment from the 1984 Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] The LA84 Foundation's mission is to promote and expand youth sports opportunities in Southern California and to increase knowledge of sport and its impact on people's lives.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1984-summer-olympics] Since inception, the Foundation has invested more than $225 million in Southern California by awarding grants to youth sports organizations, initiating sports and coaching education programs, and operating the world's premier sports library.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The **1988 Summer Olympics** (Korean: 1988년 하계 올림픽), officially the **Games of the XXIV Olympiad** (제24회 올림픽경기대회) and officially branded as **Seoul 1988** (서울 1988), were an international multi-sport event held from 17 September to 2 October 1988 in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] 159 nations were represented at the games by a total of 8,391 athletes (6,197 men and 2,194 women).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] 237 events were held and 27,221 volunteers helped to prepare the Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The 1988 Seoul Olympics were the second summer Olympic Games held in Asia, after the 1964 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, and the first held in South Korea.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The 1988 Seoul Olympics was also the last summer Olympic Games that took place during the Cold War.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] As the host country, South Korea ranked fourth overall, winning 12 gold medals and 33 medals in the competition.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] 11,331 media (4,978 written press and 6,353 broadcasters) showed the Games all over the world.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] These were the last Olympic Games of the Cold War, as well as for the Soviet Union and East Germany, as both ceased to exist before the next Olympic Games in 1992.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at the 1988 Games, with 55 and 132 respectively.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] East Germany was second, and the United States third.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Compared to the 1980 Summer Olympics (Moscow) and the 1984 Summer Olympics (Los Angeles), which were divided into two camps by ideology, the 1988 Seoul Olympics was a competition in which the boycotts virtually disappeared, although they were not completely over.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] A boycott of the 1988 Seoul Olympics took place, with North Korea along with its allies Cuba, Ethiopia, Nicaragua, and Madagascar taking part.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Albania and the Seychelles did not respond to invitations sent by the IOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Nonetheless, the much larger boycotts seen in the three previous editions were avoided, resulting in the largest number of participating nations during the Cold War era.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] For South Korea, the 1988 Olympics was a symbolic milestone that elevated its international standing while fostering national pride.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Only thirty five years after the devastation of the Korean War, and following decades of authoritarian rule and social unrest which concluded with the June Democratic Struggle just a year earlier, the games were staged successfully.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The event was regarded as the peak of the "Miracle on the Han River".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In 1999, 11 years after the games, the IOC returned to Seoul for the 109th IOC Session, which saw Turin elected as the host city for the 2006 Winter Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Seoul was chosen to host the Summer Games through a vote held on 30 September 1981, finishing ahead of Nagoya, Japan.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The awarding to Seoul was internationally considered to be surprising, with Nagoya having been considered a favourite.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Below was the vote count that occurred at the 84th IOC Session and 11th Olympic Congress in Baden-Baden, West Germany.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Seoul had previously hosted many international events, but the most noteworthy ones were the Miss Universe 1980 and the 1986 Asian Games, thus demonstrating that it had the appropriate capability.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Live doves were released during the opening ceremony as a symbol of world peace, but a number of the doves were burned alive or suffered major trauma by the lighting of the Olympic cauldron.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] As a result of protests following the incident, the last time live doves were released during the opening ceremony was in 1992 in Barcelona, at the start of the ceremony.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Balloon doves were released in 1994 Winter Olympics and the 1998 Winter Olympics and paper doves were used at the Atlanta Ceremony in 1996.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] These were also the last Summer Olympic Games to hold the opening ceremony during the daytime.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony featured a skydiving team descending over the stadium and forming the five-colored Olympic Rings, as well as a mass demonstration of taekwondo.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The skydiving team trained at SkyDance SkyDiving and had hoped the opening ceremony appearance would set the stage for skydiving becoming a medal event by 2000.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The idea for South Korea to place a bid for the 1988 Games emerged during the last days of the Park Chung Hee administration in the late 1970s, as hosting the Olympics was a big opportunity to bring international attention to South Korea.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] But before that, it was necessary to prove the country's capacity, as South Korea was seen as an exotic and risky destination for large events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The project continued to run even after President Park's assassination in 1979.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Further, he hoped it would provide protection from increasing threats from North Korea, and showcase the economic strength that the country was experiencing to the world.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Seoul was awarded the bid on 30 September 1981, becoming the 16th nation in the Summer Olympics, as well as the second Asian nation (following Japan in the 1964 Summer Olympics) and the first mainland Asian nation to host the Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Influenced by the model of 1964 Summer Olympics held in Tokyo, which served as a rite of passage for the Japanese economy and re-integration of Japan in the international community in the post-war era, the South Korean government hoped to use the Olympics as a "coming-out party".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The Olympics gave a powerful impetus to the development of South Korea's relations with Eastern Europe, the Soviet Union and with China.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In January 1982, South Korea's curfew that had been in place since 1945 was lifted.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In utilizing media events theory, Larson and Park investigated the Seoul Olympics as a form of political communication.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] They revealed the significance of South Korea's military government throughout the period of the Olympic bid and preparation, followed by the many advantages of the hosting the Games: rapid economic modernization, social mobilization and the legitimization of the military dictatorship.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Existing camps for "vagrants" (homeless persons) were ramped up before the 1988 Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] An Associated Press article states that homeless people and alcoholics, "but mostly children and the disabled" were arrested and sent to these camps to prepare for the Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In 1975, the previous president of South Korea had begun a policy of rounding up vagrants.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] According to government documents obtained by the Associated Press, from 1981 to 1986 the number of people held increased from 8,600 to more than 16,000.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Police officers often received promotions based on the number of vagrants they had arrested, and owners of facilities received a subsidy based on the number of people held.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] There were multiple reports of inmates raped or beaten, and sometimes beaten to death.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] 4,000 of these "vagrants" were held at the Brothers Home facility.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Many of the guards were former inmates who had been "promoted" because of loyalty to the camp's owner.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Various money-making operations were conducted such as manufacturing ball-point pens and fishing hooks, as well as clothing for Daewoo.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Only a few inmates were paid belatedly for this work.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] By accident while on a hunting trip, prosecutor Kim Yong-won heard about and visited a work detail of prisoners in ragged clothes overseen by guards with wooden bats and dogs.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In his words, he knew immediately that "a very serious crime" was occurring, and in January 1987, he led a raid on the facility and found beaten and malnourished inmates.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] He was politically pressured at various levels to reduce the charges against the owner, managers, and guards.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In the end, the owner only served 2+1⁄2 years in prison.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The Brothers Home was a religious facility based on the Christian faith.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] There were, in fact, inspections by both city officials and church officials.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] However, these were scheduled inspections in which healthier inmates were presented in carefully planned and orchestrated circumstances.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In the 1990s, construction workers found about 100 human bones on a mountainside outside the location of the former Brothers Home.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Victims of the Brothers Home are seeking a government investigation into the crimes committed and accountability.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The games were boycotted by North Korea and its allies Cuba, Nicaragua, Ethiopia, and Madagascar.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] North Korea had insisted upon co-hosting the Games, something that had been encouraged by Cuban president Fidel Castro, who called for North Korea to be considered joint host of the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] On 8 and 9 January 1986 in Lausanne, Switzerland, the IOC President chaired a meeting of the North and South Korean Olympic Committees.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] North Korea demanded that eleven of the 23 Olympic sports be carried out on its territory, special opening and closing ceremonies, and a joint organizing committee and a united team.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The negotiations were continued into another meeting, but were not successful.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] North Korea then announced its boycott on September 3, 1988.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The North Korean Central News Agency stated "this will leave another stain on Olympic history", and that "the 24th Olympic Games will be inevitably another crippled Olympiad where not all Olympic member states will participate".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Nicaragua had previously announced its intention to boycott on May 20, 1987.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Moises Hassan Morales, the Nicaraguan NOC president, stated "if the 1988 Olympics are not carried out in Pyongyang and Seoul, the two Korean capitals, Nicaragua will not attend this event".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Cuba made its boycott announcement on January 16, 1988, where it stated "Cuba deeply laments this decision, but our people and our athletes live by profound ethical norms and a great sense of honor".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Ethiopia announced on January 20, 1988, that it would boycott the 1988 Summer Olympics in solidarity with North Korea, Cuba, Nicaragua, and Madagascar, which had all criticized the decision disallowing North Korea to jointly organize the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee (SLOOC) closed the receipt of final entry applications for athletics on September 8, 1988.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Among the 161 NOCs which officially notified their intention to participate in the Olympics, Madagascar failed to send in an entry form by the closing date, thus, its athletes did not compete at the Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] According to the SLOOC, Madagascar did this "in support of North Korea's co-hosting request".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Albania and the Seychelles did not respond to the invitations sent by the IOC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee (SLOOC) also produced and distributed an official song of the Seoul Games to publicize the Games to all National Olympic Committees, encouraging their participation and consolidating the idea of harmony and friendship of the entire world through the song.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] "Hand in Hand" was commissioned for the Italian composer Giorgio Moroder and the American songwriter Tom Whitlock, and was performed by local group Koreana.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] E Existing facilities modified or refurbished in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] N New facilities constructed in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] According to *The Oxford Olympics Study* data is not available to establish the cost of the Seoul 1988 Summer Olympics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The cost of the stadium was 491 billion won, approximately US$354 million.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The 1988 Summer Olympics featured 23 different sports encompassing 31 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 237 events.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Badminton and bowling were held as exhibition sports, which did not require IOC approval and were not part of the official Olympic schedule.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Note: between May 8 and October 9, 1988, all the clocks in the country were advanced by one hour as a test of the possibility of adopting the daylight summer time in the country in the future.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] This advance also enabled the development of a sports calendar in which the main events were scheduled to be broadcast in major Western markets in television prime time.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Athletes from 160 nations competed at the Seoul Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Aruba, American Samoa, Brunei, Cook Islands, Maldives, Vanuatu, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, and South Yemen made their first Olympic appearance at these Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Guam made their first Summer Olympic appearance at these games having participated in the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1988 Games.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The official mascot for the 1988 Summer Olympic Games was Hodori.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] It was a stylized tiger designed by Kim Hyun as an amicable Amur tiger, portraying the friendly and hospitable traditions of the Korean people.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Hodori's female version was called Hosuni.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The name 호돌이 *Hodori* was chosen from 2,295 suggestions sent in by the public.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] It is a compound of 호 *ho*, the Sino-Korean bound morpheme for "tiger" (appearing also in the usual word 호랑이 *horangi* for "tiger"), and 돌이 *dori*, a diminutive for "boys".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] In the United States, NBC became the telecast provider hereafter for the Summer Games, after a five-Olympics run by the American Broadcasting Company from 1968 to 1984.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] NBC's coverage was their first sporting event to feature the new Quantel Cypher to generate the on-screen graphics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] However, the network would continue to use Chyron Corporation for the rest of the year with Quantel being used again for the 1988 World Series.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The Cypher would be implemented permanently starting with Super Bowl XXIII in January 1989.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Bronchodilators are also found in cold medication.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Due to the rules, his case could have led to disqualification from the Seoul Olympics and suspension from competition for six months.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The levels of the combined stimulants registered in the separate tests were 2 ppm, 4 ppm and 6 ppm.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Lewis defended himself, claiming that he had accidentally consumed the banned substances.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] After the supplements that he had taken were analyzed to prove his claims, the USOC accepted his claim of inadvertent use, since a dietary supplement he ingested was found to contain "Ma huang", the Chinese name for Ephedra (ephedrine is known to help weight loss).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] Fellow Santa Monica Track Club teammates Joe DeLoach and Floyd Heard were also found to have the same banned stimulants in their systems, and were cleared to compete for the same reason.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The highest level of the stimulants Lewis recorded was 6 ppm, which was regarded as a positive test in 1988 but is now regarded as negative test.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] The acceptable level has been raised to ten parts per million for ephedrine and twenty-five parts per million for other substances.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/1988-summer-olympics] According to the IOC rules at the time, positive tests with levels lower than 10 ppm were cause of further investigation but not immediate ban.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The **International Vocal Competition 's-Hertogenbosch** (**IVC**); is a music competition for classical singing founded in 1954.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] It is the only classical vocal competition in the Netherlands that also focuses on opera, oratorio and Lied.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] This yearly event is organised by the International Vocal Competition 's-Hertogenbosch (IVC).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The IVC is a member of the World Federation of International Music Competitions since 1959.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The IVC offers singers the chance to perform for casting directors, concert managements, impresarios, the media and a concert and theatregoing audience.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] Alongside its competition, the IVC also presents master classes, workshops, summer schools and concerts.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] Concerts are organised in collaboration with various organisations.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The IVC also provides advice on repertoire, career possibilities, media management and auditioning.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The IVC has helped launch the careers of many internationally renowned singers (see List of notable IVC alumni).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] Annett Andriesen, herself an opera singer and a prizewinner of the IVC in 1975, was head of the IVC from 2008 until 2018.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] She has since been replaced by Ivan van Kalmthout.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] From 1 September 2023, British countertenor Andrew Watts has been appointed General and artistic director of the IVC.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The IVC is open to singers of all nationalities who have had conservatory training or have reached an equivalent level.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The competition has two categories: Opera/oratorio and Lied Duo.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The 58th International Vocal Competition Theater in Song will be held from 25 - 28 September at Theater aan de Parade in 's-Hertogenbosch, Netherlands.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The IVC offers young and talented singers the chance to perform for an international jury, casting directors, concert managements, impresarios, the media and public.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-international-vocal-competition] The total prize money of the Theatre in Song competition amounts to €32.500.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-oost-railway-station] The station was opened in 1987 and is located on the Brabantselijn (Nijmegen - Tilburg).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-oost-railway-station] The train services are operated by Nederlandse Spoorwegen.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-oost-railway-station] The main station of 's-Hertogenbosch is 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch station opened on 1 November 1868 as the northern terminus of the southern part of the Utrecht–Boxtel railway (*Staatslijn H*), with service south to Boxtel.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Only in 1870 were the two parts of Line H joined, allowing for direct service to Utrecht Centraal.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] As the town was a fortress at the time, the station was designed with attack in mind; its wood truss construction allowed it to be dismantled or damaged with minimal waste.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch station was further expanded upon the opening of the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway, making it an important railway junction.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] In 1896, the original station was replaced with a large brick structure designed by Eduard Cuypers.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The station was relocated a few hundred metres south of the original, along with the realignment of the tracks to the west.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The second 's-Hertogenbosch station was characterised by its neo-Renaissance style, with a second floor for railway employees.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] During World War II, at 16 September 1944, the station caught fire and burnt down; it was never rebuilt to its former glory.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] A more modern, post-war building designed by Sybold van Ravesteyn was erected in 1951.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The remaining parts of the second building were incorporated, while the third station's canopy remains to this day.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch was again rebuilt in 1998, with an extension of the roof to the other island platform.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Much of the renovation consisted of an aerial walkway, the Stationspasserelle, connecting the roadways on either side of the tracks, and the removal of a special ramp to the platforms.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The station is an important interchange station, with trains coming from several different directions.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch was the only Dutch station which provided in Auto-Train services.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Services ran into Avignon, Bologna and Livorno.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Auto-Trains were operated by Euro-Express-Traincharter.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] There are 13 city bus lines, which are all operated by Arriva.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city's official name is a contraction of the (archaic) Dutch *des Hertogen bosch* ('the forest of the duke').
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The duke in question was Henry I, Duke of Brabant, whose family had owned a large estate at nearby Orthen for at least four centuries.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] He founded a new town located on some forested dunes in the middle of a marsh.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] At age 26, he granted 's-Hertogenbosch city rights and the corresponding trade privileges in 1185.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This is the traditional date given by later chroniclers; the first mention in contemporaneous sources is 1196.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] His reason for founding the city was to protect his own interests against encroachment from Gelre and Holland; from its first days, he conceived of the city as a fortress.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was destroyed in 1203 in a joint expedition of Gelre and Holland, but was soon rebuilt.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Some remnants of the original city walls remain.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the late 14th century, a much larger wall was erected to protect the greatly expanded settled area.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Artificial waterways were dug to serve as a city moat, through which the rivers Dommel and Aa were diverted.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch became the birthplace and home of northern Renaissance painter Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1520, the city flourished, becoming the second largest population centre in the territory of the present Netherlands, after Utrecht.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city was also a center of music, and composers, such as Jheronimus Clibano, received their training at its churches.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Others held positions there: Matthaeus Pipelare was musical director at the Confraternity of Our Lady; and renowned Habsburg copyist and composer Pierre Alamire did much of his work at 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The wars of the Reformation changed the course of the city's history.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] During the Eighty Years' War, the city took the side of the Habsburg (Catholic) authorities and thwarted a Calvinist coup.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was besieged several times by Prince Maurice of Orange, stadtholder of most of the Dutch Republic, who wanted to bring 's-Hertogenbosch under the rule of the rebel United Provinces.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city was successfully defended against Prince Maurice in 1601 and again in 1603, but it eventually fell in the 1629 siege led by his brother Frederick Henry.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the years of Truce, before the renewed fighting after 1618, the fortifications were greatly expanded.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The surrounding marshes made a siege of the conventional type impossible, and the fortress, deemed impregnable, was nicknamed *moerasdraak*, or the Swamp Dragon.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The town was nevertheless finally conquered by Frederik Hendrik of Orange in 1629 in a typically Dutch stratagem: he diverted the rivers Dommel and Aa, created a polder by constructing a forty-kilometre (25 mile) dyke and then pumped out the water by mills.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] After a siege of three months, the city had to surrender—an enormous blow to Habsburg geo-political strategy during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This surrender cut the town off from the rest of the duchy and the area was treated by the Republic as an occupation zone without political liberties (see also Generality Lands).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] After the Peace of Westphalia, the fortifications were again expanded.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1672, the Dutch *rampjaar*, the city held against the army of Louis XIV of France.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1794 French revolutionary troops under the command of Charles Pichegru attacked the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was only weakly defended, and fell after a short siege.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Pichegru then crossed the rivers and put an end to the Dutch Republic.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Under the new Batavian Republic, established in 1795, both Catholics and *Brabanders* at last gained equal rights.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] From 1806, the city became part of the Kingdom of Holland and from 1810, it was incorporated into the First French Empire.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was captured by the Prussians in 1814.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The next year, 1815, when the United Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, it became the capital of North Brabant.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Many newer and more modern fortresses were created in the vicinity of the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] A new canal was built, the 'Zuid-Willemsvaart', which gave the city an economic impulse.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1878, it was forbidden to build outside the ramparts.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] That led to overcrowding and the highest infant mortality in the kingdom.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] At the end of the 19th century, the very conservative city government prevented industrial investment to avoid an increase in the number of workers and the establishment of educational institutions: students were regarded as disorderly.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] As a result, the relative importance of the city diminished.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] One of the few official Nazi concentration camp complexes in Western Europe outside Germany and Austria was named after 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It operated from January 1943, to September 1944 and was known to the Germans as Herzogenbusch (see List of subcamps of Herzogenbusch).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] About 30,000 inmates were interned in the complex during this time, of whom about 12,000 were Jews.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the Netherlands, this camp is known as 'Kamp Vught', because the concentration camp was actually located at a heath near Vught, a village a few kilometres south of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city was occupied by German forces during World War II from 1940 to 1944.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The railway station was bombed by planes of the Royal Air Force on 16 September 1944.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city was liberated between 24 and 27 October 1944 during Operation Pheasant by British soldiers of Major-General Robert Knox Ross's 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division following the victory of the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment, of 158th Infantry Brigade over the enemy on 23–24 October.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] After the war, 's-Hertogenbosch was modernized, like many other cities in the Netherlands.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was possible that it was only the geography that shielded the old town from rigorous reconstruction in those early years.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Just in time, the pendulum swung back to protecting the history of the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1956, the council wanted to demolish the Moriaan, the oldest brick building in the Netherlands, to give traffic better access to the market square.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The permit was refused by the government and instead the building was restored, starting in 1963.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Later, city councils became much more aware of the value of historic buildings and from about the turn of the millennium, the historic fortifications are also given much attention by the authorities.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The population centres in the municipality are: Bokhoven, Crevecoeur, Deuteren (former village), Dieskant, Empel, Engelen, Gewande, 's-Hertogenbosch, Hintham, Kruisstraat, Maliskamp, Meerwijk, Orthen (former village), Oud-Empel, and Rosmalen.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Climate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Köppen Climate Classification subtype for this climate is "Cfb" (Marine West Coast Climate/Oceanic climate).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city of 's-Hertogenbosch has become a center of industry, education, administration and culture.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is currently the fourth city of North Brabant.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is home to many national and international businesses such as Heineken, Epic, Tyco International, SAP and many others.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Jeroen Bosch Hospital is the biggest employer in the area, with over 4,000 employees.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] There are also over 350 restaurants, pubs and cafés to be found in the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is also home to the European Ceramic Work Centre.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This is a juried international ceramic residency where they invite artists, designers and architects from around to the world to explore the medium of Ceramics.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This program was initially started in 1991 and continues to this day.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city has its own food speciality, the Bossche Bol—effectively a giant profiterole, somewhat larger than a tennis ball, which is filled with whipped cream and coated with chocolate.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The spoken language is Maaslands (the variant spoken in 's-Hertogenbosch is called *Bosch* which is placed among the Central North Brabantian dialects, although other classification systems also describe it as East Brabantian), which is very similar to colloquial Dutch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] De Toonzaal is a music venue for chamber music, improvised music, and experimental music.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] For popular music there is the venue W2 (or Willem II).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Noordbrabants Museum is a provincial museum with an overview of works that Vincent van Gogh made in Brabant.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Design Museum Den Bosch is a modern art museum.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Bosch Art Center, is dedicated to the work of Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Other museums include the Swan Brothers' House and Museum Slager.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Also the National (Dutch) Carnavalsmuseum Oeteldonks gemintemuzejum is located in the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the near future a new museum will be opened about the fortresses of the town and in general in Europe.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The house where the famous painter Hieronymus produced his paintings can be visited on the market square.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has a strong carnival tradition.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In its current form the story and symbolism dates from 1881 to 1883.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In these years some citizens created the legend of "Oeteldonk", whereby the city was renamed to Oeteldonk for the three day carnival.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] "Donk" is a reference to a dry place in the marsh.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The frog is widely used as a symbol during the 's-Hertogenbosch Carnival.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is also a symbol of the Oeteldonk marsh.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was also a remark aimed at Bishop Godschalk from Den Dungen, where 'Van den Oetelaar' was a common family name.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] He had wanted to forbid the traditional festivities of Shrove Tuesday that often led to excesses.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Oeteldonk is a village and therefore every inhabitant is a farmer or a '*durske*' (a girl or young woman), eliminating class differences.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The village is headed by the Mayor "Peer vaan den Muggenheuvel tot den Bobberd".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Each year the mayor of 's-Hertogenbosch hands over his authority to the Mayor of Oeteldonk.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On Sunday at 11:11 AM the Mayor of Oeteldonk then receives Prince Carnaval "Prince Amadeiro XXVI" at Oeteldonk central station.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] From there a parade of all carnival clubs escorts the company to the town hall.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The citizens of 's-Hertogenbosch wear traditional outfits throughout these days.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] A so-called *boerenkiel* is worn and every year patches are designed according to that years theme which can then be stitched onto the outfit.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The *boerenkiel* is often combined with a traditional farmers bandana and a long scarf in the colors of Oeteldonk.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The tradition of the Boerenkiel and / or Bandana is very different from the carnival traditions in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Other aspects like the parade, the temporary name and the temporary flag (for Oeteldonk red, white and yellow) are very similar.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch was founded as a fortified city and that heritage can still be seen today.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] After World War II, plans were made to modernise the old city, by filling in the canals, removing or modifying some ramparts and redeveloping historic neighbourhoods.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Before these plans could come to effect, the central government declared the city a protected townscape.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Most historic elements have been preserved.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In contrast to cities like Rotterdam, 's-Hertogenbosch also survived the Second World War relatively unscathed.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Much of its historic heritage remains intact, and today there are always renovations going on in the city to preserve the many old buildings, fortifications, churches and statues for later generations.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city center has a cosy atmosphere because of the almost continuous ramparts that still surround it.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It has been molded by the multiple rivers that convene on 's-Hertogenbosch, giving the center its strange street plan so different from the usual grid plan where streets meet at right angles.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The center is dominated by Saint John's Cathedral (*Sint-Janskathedraal* in Dutch), which dates from c.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 1220 and is best known for its Brabantine Gothic design and the many sculptures of craftsmen that are sitting on almost every arc and rim along the outside of the cathedral.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 2010 an extensive restoration was completed, undoing the damage of many years of wear-and-tear and acid rain.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On the central square is the oldest remaining brick house of the Netherlands, 'de Moriaan', which was built at the beginning of the 13th century.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the 1960s, de Moriaan was renovated to its former glory based on a famous 16th-century Dutch painting called 'De Lakenmarkt van 's-Hertogenbosch' ('The fabric market of 's-Hertogenbosch').
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The town hall is an original 14th-century Gothic building.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] After the town was conquered by the Dutch Republic in 1629, it received a new facade in the style of Dutch Baroque architecture.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It showcased the authority of the new masters, just like the new town hall in Maastricht would.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Hidden below the old city is a canal network called the Binnendieze, which once spanned 22 km (14 mi).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It started out as a regular river, the Dommel, running through the city in medieval times.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Due to a lack of space in the city, people started building their houses and roads over the river.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Later, the Binnendieze functioned as a sewer and fell into disrepair.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In recent decades, the remaining sixth part of the old waterway system has been renovated, and it is possible to take several guided subterranean boat trips through it.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has an extensive and almost complete fifteenth-to-seventeenth-century city fortification.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It was made to profit from the city's strong defensive position, lying on a sandy hill in the center of a large swamp fed by many rivers.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This also caused the main ramparts to be preserved, because they were crucial in keeping out the water.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 2004 the city was awarded the title *European Fortress City of the year*.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the years that followed it restored many of the city defenses to much of their old glory.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Apart from small sections of medieval walls, the main structure of the fortification is a late-medieval (fifteenth-century) wall.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The upper sections were removed when cannon became more powerful, and polygonal bastions were added, some after the conquest by the republic.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Most of these have not been restored to their original height, but do maintain their brick walls.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The citadel in the north west of the city does retain its original height.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Around the city itself many other fortresses can still be seen.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In the north east of the old city, the hexagonal gunpowder magazine, called *Kruithuis* is located close to the citadel.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is one of only a handful that still exist in the Netherlands, and was built when the city was still part of the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is planned to become the museum of fortress 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] One of the bastions of the fortress now houses the mini museum Bastionder.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It has been dug out in a bastion of the south side.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On the inside it shows a unique wrought iron cannon, and an older bastion that was walled in by the current one.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On the south side of the city, the city center and walls still border the Bossche Broek, an old polder that could never be made dry.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1995 the dyke of the Dommel broke and an enormous amount of water entered the polder.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It also flooded and blocked the main Dutch highway A2.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In order to prevent this in the future, the area was rearranged to store excess water in case of emergencies.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 2006 the area had been furnished with higher dikes and locks that allowed a controlled flooding of the polder and some adjacent areas in case of emergency.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Bossche Broek is now a 22-hectare (54-acre) nature reserve, that stretches all the way to Vught.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is connected to the Moerputten and Vlijmens Ven, with which it forms a Natura 2000 area.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Rare species in the area are the scarce large blue and the European weather loach.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Moerputten sports the Moerputten Bridge, a 600-metre (650 yard) long nineteenth century railway bridge and engineering feat.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] What is unique about the area is its close proximity to the city center.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city is also the location of the *Bolwoningen* complex, an array of fifty experimental spherical houses designed by Dries Kreijkamp.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Lutheran Church, 's-Hertogenbosch is no longer used as a church.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city has one professional football club, FC Den Bosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is the 1967 successor of the professional branches of BVV (Bossche Voetbal Vereniging) and Wilhelmina.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Both of them still exist as amateur football clubs.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] As a successor of BVV FC Den Bosch can claim the national championship of 1948.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This championship led to the construction of stadium De Vliert, which at one time had a capacity of 30,000.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Due to the less successful years that followed, the capacity is now only 8,500 visitors.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] FC Den Bosch was the first club of Dutch international player Ruud van Nistelrooy.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is more successful in field hockey.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The women's team in particular is a dominant force in the Dutch field hockey competition.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The professional basketball club Heroes Den Bosch is also very successful.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The city's rugby club is called The Dukes and dates from 1974.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is located at a very scenic location at the foot of the city walls.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Because of the limited space, the club plays on artificial turf and part of the accommodation is subterranean.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It became the national rugby champion in 2008.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] As regards events the city is host to the Rosmalen Grass Court Championships, a combined ATP Tour and WTA Tour grass court tennis event played two weeks before the Wimbledon Championships.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The World Archery Championships and World Para Archery Championship were held here in June 2019.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] During these combined World Championships two separate venues were used: the Parade and the rugby fields of The Dukes.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] All finals took place in the arena at the Parade.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Parade is a historic square surrounded by high trees, situated at the foot of the nearly seven-hundred-year-old Saint John's Cathedral in the attractive center of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Zuid-Willemsvaart runs from the Meuse just north of the city towards Maastricht via Helmond and Weert.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 's-Hertogenbosch it runs through the city proper, south east from where a bastion has been cut off from the citadel.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Because of this route it was impossible to widen it further than for ships of CEMT class II.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Therefore, the Máxima Canal of 8 km (5 miles) was dug just east of the city, creating a shortcut from the canal to the Meuse suitable for ships of CEMT class IV.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On the remaining part of the Zuid-Willemsvaart west of the city is the industrial harbor of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is situated on the busy A2 motorway, the most important north–south connection of the Netherlands.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This connection was established with the opening of the Dieze Bridge in 1942.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] From 1961 the Utrecht-'s-Hertogenbosch section was 2 times 2 lanes.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1970 the A2 was rerouted to the east of the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1989 it finally became a controlled-access highway.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 1996 the section between 's-Hertogenbosch and Eindhoven became a controlled-access highway.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The situation in Maastricht was only solved in 2016, when the Koning Willem-Alexandertunnel was opened.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On the east–west axis 's-Hertogenbosch is on the A59 motorway.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The A65 motorway between 's-Hertogenbosch and Tilburg is a regional highway, but is not completely access-controlled.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is on the Utrecht–Boxtel part of the railway stretch between Amsterdam and the Dutch industrial/tech center near Eindhoven.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] As a consequence north–south trains depart every ten minutes.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] On the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway trains run on a more modest schedule.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is also a major station for Arriva buslines that serve the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Other stations within the limits of the municipality are 's-Hertogenbosch Oost railway station and Rosmalen railway station.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Vught railway station is actually closer to the city center than that in Rosmalen.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has attempted to adapt to the growing popularity of the bicycle in Dutch cities.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] A reasonable amount of bike paths has so far been constructed in the town.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In 2011, the city was chosen as *Fietsstad 2011*—the top bike city of the Netherlands for 2011.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] This is a big achievement for a city where bicycle use is lower than in the rest of the Netherlands".
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has multiple vocational universities called *Hogeschool* in Dutch.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The HAS Hogeschool of about 3,500 students is focused on agricultural and food technology.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Avans Hogeschool is located in 's-Hertogenbosch and two nearby cities.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Joost is an art academy that is now part of Avans and dates back to 1812.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Fontys Hogeschool also offers some education in the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Academy of Data Science (JADS), located at the Mariënburg Campus in the center of 's-Hertogenbosch, and provides a number of data science programs at graduate (MSc) and post-graduate level (PhD).
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is a department of the Eindhoven University of Technology and Tilburg University.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] In secondary education the City Gymnasium is a gymnasium (school) that originated from the Latin school of the city.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is comparable to a grammar school and can trace its origin back 1274.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The same type of education and all other types of secondary education are offered by a number of large institutes.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion in 's-Hertogenbosch, with somewhat more than 40% of the population counting themselves as belonging to it.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Even so, attendance at mass is significantly lower than 40%.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Three churches in the city center are still in use by the Catholic church: Saint John's Cathedral, Saint Catherine and the Monastery Church of the Franciscans nearby the railway station.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] Smaller churches in use by the Roman Catholic church are: Saint Anne's Church in Hintham, Saint Landoline Church in Empel, Saint Willibrord Church in Maaspoort, Saint Lambert Church (Rosmalen), etc.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Protestant religion has seen its share of believers in the city fall from 20% to about 4%.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Eastern Orthodox Church is a new church in town.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] It is based at Saint Catherine's Church where Catholic worship services have been held again since 2021.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Arrahma Mosque has been built by the Moroccan community.
[src:s-hertogenbosch/s-hertogenbosch] The Turkish community has the Orhan Gazi Mosque.
